{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17523511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17523511"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:56:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13903"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13903"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.3,0.43,0.07,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6522"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87110"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6522","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6522"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13903"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71368"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1948"},{"type":"tags","id":"4100"},{"type":"tags","id":"4772"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13026"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14081"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34954"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"87110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/87110"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of painless growths in his genital area. He is otherwise well. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He reports having unprotected sexual intercourse with a new partner two months ago. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Genital examination reveals multiple skin lesions on the shaft of the penis and in the perianal area (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Seborrhoeic keratoses","Condylomata lata","Condylomata acuminata","Chancroid","Genital herpes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Econdylomata acuminata\u003C/strong\u003E, commonly known as genital warts. These are caused by human papillomavirus (HPV) infection, typically types 6 and 11. The characteristic appearance of multiple soft, flesh-coloured, papillomatous growths in the anogenital region, along with the history of recent unprotected sexual intercourse, strongly supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnosis of condylomata acuminata is typically clinical, based on the characteristic appearance and location of the lesions. A biopsy can be obtained if there is uncertainty about the diagnosis, such as in cases where squamous cell carcinoma is suspected. Treatment options include patient-applied topical therapies (e.g., imiquimod, podophyllotoxin) or provider-administered therapies (e.g., cryotherapy, surgical excision). Patients should also be counselled about safe sex practices and offered screening for other sexually transmitted infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESeborrhoeic keratoses\u003C/strong\u003E are benign skin growths that typically appear as brown, waxy, stuck-on plaques. They are more common in older adults and usually occur on the trunk, face, and extremities, not in the genital area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECondylomata lata\u003C/strong\u003E is a manifestation of secondary syphilis. They appear as flat-topped, moist, grey-white or pink papules, often coalescing into plaques. They are typically broader and flatter than condylomata accuminata and are associated with other symptoms of secondary syphilis (e.g., generalised rash, lymphadenopathy).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChancroid\u003C/strong\u003E is a sexually transmitted infection caused by \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus ducreyi\u003C/em\u003E. It presents with painful genital ulcers and tender suppurative inguinal lymphadenopathy, which is not consistent with the painless growths described in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGenital herpes\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with painful vesicles or ulcers rather than painless papillomatous growths. The absence of pain and the characteristic appearance of the lesions make herpes less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Condylomata acuminata (genital warts) are caused by human papillomavirus (HPV) infection, typically types 6 and 11.","Genital warts often present as flesh-coloured, soft, papillomatous growths in the anogenital region.","Diagnosis of condylomata acuminata is typically clinical, based on characteristic appearance and location of lesions."],"references":["Plotzker RE, Vaidya A, Pokharel U, Stier EA. Sexually Transmitted Human Papillomavirus: Update in Epidemiology, Prevention, and Management. Infect Dis Clin North Am. 2023 Jun;37(2):289\u2013310. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37105644/","Mallon E. Dermatoses of Perineal and Perianal Skin. In: Rook\u2019s Textbook of Dermatology, Ninth Edition [Internet]. John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Ltd; 2016 [cited 2024 Aug 30]. p. 1\u201336. Available at: https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/9781118441213.rtd0114"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"71368"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13903"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20838"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20838","links":{"s